<DOC><DOCNO> AP880928-0246 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-28-88 0415EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   09-28 0515</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0538</SECOND><DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Electronic Data Systems has sued former chairmanRoss Perot, claiming he is violating an agreement made when he leftEDS not to compete in the same markets as his old company.   The suit filed Tuesday in Fairfax, Va. seeks an order enforcinga 1986 agreement in which Perot said he would not compete with EDSfor three years.   Alleged violations include Perot's proposal earlier this year toautomate the U.S. Postal Service. After protests by EDS and othercompanies, the General Services Administration suspended his postalcontract.</TEXT><DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   SmithKline Beckman Corp., which saw a 25percent drop in profits in the first half of 1988, has announced amajor restructuring of its pharmaceutical business that will costup to $400 million and force layoffs of 1,600 workers.   The company said Tuesday it will close its Philadelphia drugmanufacturing operation, which employs about 900 workers. U.S. andinternational drug sales and research, which had been the threemain units of the company's drug business, will be consolidated.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal appeals court has upheld a judge'sdecision to set aside a jury's verdict that the anti-nausea drugBendectin caused birth defects in the daughter of a woman who tookthe medication during pregnancy.   A three-judge panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals heresaid Tuesday that lower court judge properly rejected thescientific testimony of a expert witness who said Bendectin hadcaused the deformities to the arms and legs of Carita Richardson ofWashington.   The ruling was hailed as a significant legal development byMerrell Dow Pharmaceuticals, Inc., the company which made the drugfor nearly 20 years before stopping production in 1983 due tomounting legal costs from lawsuits.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Chrysler Corp.'s heavily hyped Car Buyer's Billof Rights may be expanded to include a 30-day money back guaranteeon new cars and trucks, the No. 3 automaker says.   The guarantee program is being tested until Nov. 20 in theWashington, D.C. area, and a 30-day vehicle-exchange program isbeing offered in the Denver area.   Chrysler tried the money-back guarantee nationwide in 1982 as itwas emerging from the brink of bankruptcy. Fewer than 1 percent ofthe cars it sold during that period were returned, a spokesman saidTuesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Oil prices could continue eroding through theyear's end as world economics encourage quota cheating by membersof the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, someeconomists say.   Economists say Tuesday's price declines, which put some crudefutures near two-year lows, were part of a predictable pattern ofgradually eroding prices through the end of 1988 as world economicsencourage continued overproduction by members of the Organizationof Petroleum Exporting Countries.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Stock prices edged lower in light trading Tuesday. The Dow Jonesaverage of 30 industrial stocks fell 2.84 to 2,082.33.   The dollar was mostly lower. Gold prices moved higher.   Bond prices fell in a quiet session.   Soybean futures advanced, but wheat futures finished slightlylower.</TEXT></DOC>